observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management: 

Require the Municipal Accountant to review the errors noted in the Cash Receipts Journal and make the necessary corrections;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that collections for Property Taxes are equally recorded under Basic and SEF Columns and review entries at the end of each month;
Explain the discrepancy of debited Deferred Real Property Tax and Deferred Special Education Tax and the amount of collections reported in the Abstract of RPT Collections from Treasury, and record necessary corrections; and
Recognize the realized property taxes from the advanced payments in 2022.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Locate and retrieve the necessary supporting documents of the receivable and liability accounts totaling ₱5,528,038.33 to determine the details of the receivable accounts and to identify those who are responsible for settling these obligations/debts with the LGU in order to establish the validity and accuracy of the respective receivable account balances presented in the financial statements; and

Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer in collecting the Due from Officers and Employees amounting to ₱335,405.00 through the issuance of demand letters to identified employees and officers and require them to settle their obligations;

We recommended to Management the following:
To instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare necessary adjusting journal entries to reclassify the noted accounting errors and corresponding depreciation to reflect the correct of the affected accounts in the Financial Statements, the proposed entries are as follows;
To require the Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere to the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Roads Asset Management System prescribed in COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015 and pertinent provisions of NGAS for LGUs;
For the Accounting Department to keep and maintain ledger and subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network using the prescribed format as mentioned in the above circular;
For the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and
For the General Services Officer to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and their components, also using the prescribed format mentioned in the above circular.
Management has expressed its full commitment to comply with the recommendations of the Audit Team. The Office of the Municipal Engineering (OME) submitted an updated list of road networks to the Accounting Office and the General Services Office (GSO). The GSO, in coordination with the OME, conducted road tagging activities in accordance with the Local Road Inventory to ensure proper identification and classification of road assets.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the following officers:
General Services Officer (GSO) to:
Consolidate the 2-month requirement for the procurement of commonly used supplies through the preparation of the consolidated PR on a bi-monthly basis based on the consolidated PPMP and APP;
Maintain an inventory record of the procured supplies under safekeeping;
Issue the necessary ICS for every issuance of such to the requesting office;
Bid and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly adopt public or competitive bidding as the primary mode of procurement, in accordance with the provisions of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of Republic Act No. 9184, to ensure transparency, accountability, and the attainment of the most advantageous terms for the government; and
Concerned department heads to stop the practice of preparing the PRs, except in duly justified emergency cases. All requisitions for commonly used supplies shall be coursed through the General Services Office (GSO), which shall be responsible for the preparation of consolidated PRs, safekeeping, and monitoring of the supplies to ensure proper inventory control and accountability.
The Management commented that the General Services Office (GSO) will implement a system to streamline the processing of PRs submitted through the official department email. All submissions will be consolidated and aligned with the APP.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the LSB in coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer to include the previous year's unexpended balances in the computation of the estimated income for the budget year;
Require the Co-chairman of the LSB to identify the schools for each PPA to be programmed under the fund for proper implementation and monitoring thereof;
Require the LSB to submit the resolution approving the SEF Budget for the year 2024 duly signed by all the members; and
Instruct the LSB to identify the correct appropriations for the two P/A/Ps with inconsistent amounts in the SEF Budget, resolution and LSB Plan and submit the revised documents submit the indicating the same amounts of the appropriations.
In their letter reply, Management commented that they included the previous year's unexpended balances in computing the estimated income and identifying schools in the SEF Budget 2025. Additionally, Management is to submit the related documents for validation by the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC and the BAC Secretariat, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, to attach Notice of Awards to the Winning Bidders to support the claims for honoraria, to ensure compliance with the documentary requirements specified in COA Circular 2012-001;
Ensure that Driver’s Trip Tickets, which must be serially numbered, are properly accomplished and consistent with the corresponding fuel slips attached to disbursement vouchers and that the concerned personnel prepare and submit the required Summary of Requisition and Issue Vouchers, Monthly Reports of Official Travels and Fuel Consumption to the Audit Team for verification and audit purposes, to effectively regulate the use of government vehicles and ensure accountability in fuel utilization;
Direct the BAC to include the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) and other terms and conditions of the items to be procured in the RFQ to obtain accurate quotations and instruct the BAC to require the suppliers, either losing or winning ones, to submit the required documents as prescribed under Appendix A, Annex H of the revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to ascertain whether the agency is transacting with suppliers of known qualifications only;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all claims related to the purchase of drugs, medicines, and medical supplies are supported with complete documentation such as utilization reports and/or distribution lists to ensure that government funds are expended for valid, proper, and legal purposes;
Instruct the GSO to prepare the maintenance/repair record of each vehicle owned and/or operated by the municipal government. Henceforth, require the repair history of motor vehicles before repair work is to be done and before payment of repair expenses; and
Direct the BAC to ensure adequacy of information provided on Purchase Orders (POs).
The Management commented that they will comply with the audit recommendations and COA Circular 2012-001 provisions.

We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendations that Management:

Require the General Services Officer to strictly comply with the required physical count of all properties at least once a year using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;
Require the General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the GSO;
Instruct the General Services Officer to  renew/update the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs)  every three years after issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability;
Direct the General Services Officer to assign personnel to affix property tags/stickers on all properties of the LGU to facilitate a methodological system of inventory-taking and to strengthen internal control on PPE; 
Require the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the General Services Officer to locate the documents of beginning balances of PPE from previous years’ transactions with a total book value of ₱136,395,995.11; and
Require the General Services Officer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to comply with the guidelines and procedures for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Coordinate with the Municipal Budget Officer to explain the discrepancies noted in the SCBAA and in the reconciliation statement, and to prepare corrected reports;
Substantiate the reconciling items in the SCBAA totaling ₱106,824,344.21 by providing supporting schedules that can be verified against the amounts presented in the financial statements;
Ensure adequate disclosure in the Notes to the Financial Statements regarding the reconciling items in the SCBAA reconciliation and non-cash transactions under the indirect method of presenting Operating Activities. This should include narrative description and detailed analyses that were omitted in the financial statements.
Prepare the Operating Activities under the Indirect Method in accordance with the provisions of IPSAS 2 to present accurate and reliable financial statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Reorganize the Property and Equipment Inventory Committee (PEIC);
Direct the General Services Officer to take appropriate action in maintaining Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and reconcile them accordingly with the Property Cards maintained GSO;
Begin the process of complying with the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the assertions regarding the existence, condition, and valuation of the PPE accounts.
We further recommended that upon reorganization of the Property and Equipment Inventory Committee (PEIC) the Local Chief Executive ensure that:
A physical count of all properties will be conducted at least once a year to prepare the RPCPPE to be submitted to the Audit Team; and
Unserviceable properties of the Municipality will be inspected to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable. Properties (IRRUP) and the Waste Materials Report (WMR) to be submitted to the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the LSB to require the necessary, complete, proper, accurate and timely reports, data and information from concerned officials/employees to come up with the SEF plan and budget that is compliant with JC No. 1, Series of 2017;
Require the PSDS or co-chairman of the LSB to properly prepare the SEF Budget using the prescribed form by filling out all the necessary details and to specifically identify the PPAs to be programmed under the fund for proper implementation and monitoring thereof;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to secure authority from LSB through Resolution prior to the utilization of generic appropriations stated in the SEF budget;
Instruct the LSB to utilized funds for ECCD Program in the SEF Budget.

For the Municipality to have the assurance that inventories are safeguarded against the risk of misapplication or misuse, we recommend that the Municipal Mayor through the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer of the following:
Record inventory using the prescribed perpetual method of accounting on all purchased supplies and materials and use inventory tags or stock cards for monitoring;
Require the GSO and the Office of the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain complete SCs and SLCs, respectively, and reconcile their records regularly to ensure that all purchases and issuances are properly accounted for;
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct a comprehensive physical count of all types of inventory items semestrally prepare the RPCI and submit the same to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively. Also, invite representative from the COA to act as witness in the physical count; and
Submit on a quarterly basis Report on Supplies and Materials Issued to the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:
Require from the Accountable Officers who are signatories to the Acceptance and Inspection Report to double check and verify the items delivered with the Purchase Order and Purchase Request to prevent over and under deliveries and before signing thereon;
Ensure that only those items with the same specifications and price as that stated in the Purchase Order be received;
Absolutely stop the practice of receiving deliveries from the supplier or contractor without accomplishing the necessary documents for complete documentation; and
The Accountable Officers are completely enjoined from signing the IAR in the event the supplier or contractor has failed to make the deliveries in full.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the former BAC in coordination with the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents for audit to support the validity of disbursements and ensure that all supporting documents of the contract are properly prepared, signed, and dated;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to undertake the following courses of action:

To ensure that additional retention money shall be deducted after the 50% completion when the project is not satisfactorily done and not on schedule (with a negative slippage) based on the Statement of Work Accomplished and Statement of Time Elapsed and Accomplished;

To recognize the recoupment of advance payment to contractors by deducting 15 percent from periodic progress payments in all infrastructure projects; 

To ensure that tax shall only be deducted on every progress billing based on work accomplished, hence the 15% mobilization (advances to contractors) is not taxable;

To take up the proposed adjusting journal entries to present the accurate balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements; and

To deduct accordingly the overpayment of ₱1,576,984.64 from the payment of subsequent or final billing of the contractor.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to use appropriate accounts in recognizing the purchase of goods held for distribution;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the misclassification of accounts and non-recording of the remaining goods for distribution;

Require the GSO to submit an Invoice Receipt of Property as proof of transfer of the laptop and printer to the DepEd to be the basis of the Municipal Accountant to record the issuance thereof; and

Direct the GSO to prepare Acknowledgement Receipts instead of Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) to support the distribution of goods to the intended beneficiaries.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the co-chairman of the LSB to prepare the SEF Budget using the required SEF Budget Preparation Form which shall be presented by program, project and activity and by allotment class and per school;

Ensure that the utilization of the SEF Budget is in accordance with the Local School Board Resolution duly approved by the majority of all LSB members, and not by the Sangguniang Bayan;

Inform the division superintendent of schools in writing on the designation of the district supervisor who shall serve as co-chairman of the municipal school board;

Instruct the co-chairman of the LSB to sign the Obligation Request and in the “Box A” portion of the Disbursement Voucher to certify that charges to SEF budget are necessary, lawful and under their direct supervision, and also to certify that supporting documents are valid, proper and legal. Likewise, the co-chairman shall sign in the Purchase Request as the requester of goods to be procured.

Direct the co-chairman of the LSB to specifically identify PPAs to be implemented per school and if generic terms were used there should be a prior authorization from the LSB through a resolution for its utilization.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Instruct the Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO) to prepare Contracts of Agreement to all Job Order personnel duly signed by both parties;

Direct the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the HRMO to ensure that all payrolls of JO and COS personnel are duly supported with verified/accepted Individual Accomplishment Report indicating the specific tasks accomplished for each period covered;

Require the HRMO to immediately coordinate with the PhilHealth Office for the coverage of those directly hired casual and JOs under the Group Enrollment Scheme to ensure that the casual and JOs personnel have access to quality and cost-effective health care services.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the General Services Officer to prepare Pre-Repair Evaluation Report, before purchasing the materials needed for repairs and maintenance, to be signed by the Technical Inspector and attested or noted by the Department Head, with the following details:

Inspection Report No.;
Date Requested;
Date Inspected and Evaluated;
Property for Repair;
Type of Repair/Defects Noted; and
Detailed estimates of materials needed

Instruct the General Services Officer to prepare Post-Repair Inspection Report based on the Pre-Repair Evaluation Report to prove that repairs and maintenance have been completed. It is to be signed by the Technical Inspector, and attested or noted by the Department Head, with the following details:

Inspection Report No.;
Date Requested;
Date Inspected;
Purchase Request No. with the corresponding Approved Budget;
Purchase Order No. with the corresponding Amount to be paid;
Remarks of the Technical Inspector as to the completion of the repairs and maintenance made.
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all payments for various repairs and maintenance are duly supported with Pre-Repair Evaluation Reports and Post-Repair Inspection Reports.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to support the result of the physical inventory-taking of PPEs. As a rule, the RPCPPE is to be  submitted the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year,  pursuant to Section 124, Volume I, NGAS Manual;
Require the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer (GSO) to update and reconcile PPE ledger cards and Property Cards;
Instruct the GSO to  renew/update the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs)  every three years after issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability;
Direct the Inventory Committee to affix property tags to each property and equipment during the physical inventory-taking for proper control and monitoring. Adopt the property identification system prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Property and equipment costing ₱15,000.00 and below be dropped from  PPE accounts because these are semi-expendable items which are to be recognized as expenses. These are to be supported by Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for the purpose of monitoring, control and accountability;
Require the GSO to ensure that all identified unserviceable property and equipment be reported in the Inventory and Inspection of Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP).  Ensure that COA inspection be requested for  its disposal; and
Instruct the GSO, Municipal Accountant and Inventory/Disposal Committee to comply strictly with   COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the implementation of one-time cleansing of PPE accounts.
Management commented that the recommendation of the Audit Team is well   taken. The Audit Team was also informed on the following actions undertaken by Management, to wit:
Since the creation of Property and Equipment Inventory Committee (PEIC) on April 26, 2021, the committee has started to conduct inventory of PPE where the result was reported in Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE). The report was submitted to this office on April 6, 2022.
PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards are kept updated at the General Services Office, and reconciliation with the Accounting Office is still on going.
The GSO has started compiling Property Acknowledgment Receipts (PARs) since July 2019. Copies are provided to this office. The same shall be renewed/updated this coming July 2022.
All PPEs have their property tags for proper control and monitoring, which are being affixed during the acceptance of the same by the accepting-office/ department. The PEIC will start updating the same to adopt the property identification system prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.
PPEs costing ₱15,000.00 below are now dropped from PPE accounts as they are considered semi-expandable items. These are supported by the Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for monitoring, control and accountability.
All unserviceable properties and equipment are now recorded and reported in the Inventory and Inspection of Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP). A copy thereof was submitted to the audit team. It was also assured that the GSO shall request the COA for inspection before said unserviceable PPEs are disposed.
The GSO, the Municipal Accountant and the Property and Equipment Inventory Committee (PEIC)/ Property and Equipment Disposal Committee (PEDC) shall strictly comply with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the implementation of one-time cleansing of PPE accounts.

We recommended  that the Local Chief Executive:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert diligent effort to locate the necessary documents to support the preparation of aging schedule of liability accounts. This will facilitate to identify dormant payable accounts for write-off when confirmed to be non-moving for more than six (6) years;
Require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify accordingly all accounts not properly classified in the books of accounts. Ensure that financial transactions were recorded and classified in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015;
Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile the balances of Goodwill Money collected from Public Market Phase 1 and Public Market Phase 2 with the Cash in Bank account balance and cashbook  for each fund, and  to effect adjustments accordingly;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to refund to the source agencies all unexpended/unutilized balances of all fund transfers for completed projects;
Direct the Human Resource Management Officer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile with GSIS relative to the unremitted personal and government shares of LGU employees;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to remit salary loan amortization of employees to the lending institutions; and
Reconcile all unremitted shares with NMIS and DPWH, and remit accordingly all shares due them.
Management commented that persons responsible were directed and instructed by the Municipal Mayor to comply with the foregoing recommendations of the Audit Team.

11.11   We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the BAC to invite representatives from National Association of Contractors duly recognized by the Construction Industry Authority of the Philippines and Non-Government Organization (NGO) as observers in the procurement activities consistent with the requirements of Section 13.1 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
Require the BAC to instruct bidders to use the bidding documents  prescribed in the 6th Edition of Philippine Bidding Documents (PBDs);
Instruct the BAC, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents to establish the validity and propriety of the transaction.
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to submit a written explanation/justification on charging the Renovation of the Auxiliary Mayor’s Office and Waiting Area under MOOE instead of Capital Outlay.
Management agreed to comply with the audit recommendations. Invitation of representatives from the National Association of Contractors shall be complied with. A memorandum was issued to the BAC, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to submit lacking documents, and to the Municipal Budget Officer to submit written explanation / justification on charging the said project under MOOE instead of Capital Outlay.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the BAC to invite observers from duly organized group and Non-Government Organization (NGO) in the procurement activities pursuant to the requirements of Sections 13.1 and 13.2 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
Require the BAC members to use the prescribed bidding documents in conformity with the 6th Edition of Philippine Bidding Documents, and emphasize to the bidders the possibility of non-acceptance of bid for non-compliance therewith;
Require the BAC to instruct the BAC-TWG to observe strictly the guidelines in the conduct and preparation of Post-Qualification Reports to establish properly the eligibility of the participating bidders;
Management commented that the Local Chief Executive:
Required the BAC to ensure that observers shall be invited from the duly organized group and non-government organizations at least 5 CDs before the date of procurement activity.
Required the BAC to issue bidding documents in accordance with the 6th Edition of Philippine Bidding Documents provided by the GPPB.
Directed the BAC Secretariat, TWG, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team all lacking documents relative to the projects.

We also recommended that Management:

a.	Reconcile the physical inventory report with accounting records/reports to determine any discrepancy. Accountable personnel be held accountable for the missing PPEs; 



b.	Submit a copy of the Inventory Report to COA not later than January 31of each year; 



c.	Require the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer (GSO) to maintain/update the PPE ledger cards and Property Cards, respectively;


d.	Instruct the GSO to  maintain/update the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs) to be renewed every three years or every time there is a change in custodianship/user of the property;

e.	Affix property tags to each property and equipment during the physical inventory-taking for proper control and monitoring;

f.	Require the GSO to make use of Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) in the issuance of semi-expendable items (such as punchers, staplers, scissors, etc.,) for proper accountability and control; 

g.	Ensure that all identified unserviceable property and equipment be reported in the Inventory and Inspection of Report of Unserviceable Property which is the basis to reclassify the same to Other Assets account pending its disposal and to request for inspection  to COA for disposal of the unserviceable properties and equipment; and 

h.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment to Other Assets account while awaiting its final disposal to ensure a reliable presentation of PPE accounts in the interim financial reports.

i.	Submit Monthly Report on PPE Purchases  with the following data to be prepared by the General Services Officer:


j.	Submit Monthly Report on Semi-Expendable Purchases with the following data to be prepared by a designated Supply Officer.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive  implement the following: 

 Instruct the Municipal Accountant to - 

Maintain individual subsidiary ledger for all accounts, as required under Sections 111 and 114 PD No. 1445 to provide vital information or details of the transactions;

Exert diligent effort to locate the necessary supporting documents in order to prepare an ageing schedule of liability accounts that would reflect the correct ageing of payables/liability per transaction;

Reclassify accordingly all accounts which were not properly classified in the books of the Municipality; and  



Submit explanation on why the Schedule balances of Goodwill Money from Public Market Phase 1 and Public Marked Phase 2 did not reconcile with the Cash in Bank account balance maintained for each fund; and to reconcile the book balance of each fund with the Cash in Bank account to determine the discrepancies noted and effect adjustments, if necessary;

Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant  to obtain a copy of Memorandum of Agreement to support the fund transfer  and to provide basis for  the utilization of funds. 

Ensure that fund transfer from DOH be utilized for the implementation of intended projects, programs or activities; and any unexpended balance of fund transfer shall be settled pursuant to the Memorandum of Agreement and COA Circular No. 94-013.

We reiterate our audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Accountant to:
Locate the necessary supporting documents in order to determine the exact/actual date of the receivable accounts;
Identify the LGUs and NGAs, and individuals/entities obliged to settle  obligations/debts with the LGU to establish the validity and accuracy of   the respective receivable account balances presented in the financial statements;
Observe the guidelines and procedures in requesting write-off of accounts as provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 when these accounts are confirmed to be non-moving for ten (10) years or more, and were considered to be dormant accounts; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to send confirmation and demand letters to identified employees, individuals and offices that have existing account with the LGU.

We recommended that Management undertakes the following courses of action:
The accounting and supply records be updated and reconciled periodically to come up with a reliable and fair presentation of inventory accounts in the financial statements;
Ensure that a physical count be conducted on inventory items at least once a year and the result of the physical count be reported in the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) which shall be submitted to the  Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and

We recommended that Management strictly comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Roads Asset Management System prescribed in COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015.
We also recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary records for road and road components for every road network, and to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system;
Require the General Services Officer, to maintain a Report of the Local Road Network and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with complete description of and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and
Create an inventory committee to conduct the physical count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System.

We reiterate our audit recommendations  that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Exert diligent effort to locate the supporting documents necessary to prepare an ageing schedule of liability accounts that would reflect the correct ageing of payables/liability per transaction;
Reclassify accordingly all accounts  not properly classified in the books of accounts;
Reconcile the schedule balances of Goodwill Money from Public Market Phase 1 and Public Marked Phase 2 with the Cash in Bank account balance  for each fund; and  effect adjustments accordingly;
Revert unliquidated balances of accounts payable which has been outstanding for two years or more and against which no actual claim, administrative or judicial, has been filed or which is not covered by perfected contracts on record. However, this shall not apply to unliquidated balances of accounts payable in trust funds as long as the purposes for which the funds were created have not been accomplished; and
Transfer all fees and interest income to the General Fund for additional funding of municipal expenditures, thus, subject for appropriation.

To address the foregoing issues, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive undertake the following:
Require the Contractor concerned to refund the cost difference in the total amount of ₱85,676.01 and ₱89,589.93 due to non-installation of some materials;
Comply with the Technical Specification of electric meter installed to avoid the issuance of Notice of Disallowance;
Require the Contractor to submit the Delivery Receipt and Charge/Sales Invoice to be submitted to the Audit Team; and
Submit dated Inspection and Acceptance Report

We recommended that Management require the BAC, BAC Secretariat, and TWG to:
Invite observers in the procurement activities consistent with the requirements of Section 13 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
Post the Notice of Award, Contract and Notice to Proceed in the agency website;
Require Bids and Award Committee to issue the bidding documents in accordance with the 6th Edition of Philippine Bidding Documents provided by the GPPB to bidders and emphasize the possibility of non-acceptance of bid for non-compliance therewith;
Instruct the winning bidder to post Performance Security within ten calendar days from receipt of the Notice of Award and prior to the signing of the contract.
Require the Municipal Accountant to deduct the 10 retention money from the progress billing of the contractor pursuant to Section 6.1, Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and
We recommended that Management instruct the BAC Chairman, BAC Secretariat, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to submit the aforementioned lacking documents to establish the validity and propriety of the transaction, and to submit comments/justifications on the deficiencies noted.
We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant ensure that the required supporting documents are complete before affixing her signature on the voucher and effecting payment.

We recommended that Management undertake the following actions in the disposal of unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment, to wit:
Direct the GSO to report all unserviceable property and equipment of the LGU in the IIRUP. Ensure that the said report be duly accomplished;
Create a Disposal/Appraisal Committee to administer and manage the disposal process;
Ensure that the unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment be disposed pursuant to Section 79 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 89-296 dated January 27, 1989.  Likewise, be guided accordingly with the guidelines set forth under Chapter 7 of the Training Handbook on Property & Supply Management System in the appraisal and disposal of properties; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment to Other Assets account while awaiting its final disposal to ensure a reliable presentation of PPE accounts in the interim financial reports.

We have recommended that Management:

a.	Advise the SB officials concerned to stop the practice of incurring disbursements for meals during meetings, committee/public hearings and sessions, if the meals and snacks is so necessary, it should be charged against their Representation Allowances;



b.	Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Officials concerned to stop the practice of reimbursement of expenses, instead direct payment should be made to the supplier thru issuance of check;



c.	Require the Municipal Accountant to record expenses  in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts; and


d.	Submit justification why the expenses for meals and snacks during sessions, meetings and committee/hearings of the SB should not be disallowed in audit.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

         a. 	Require the Municipal Officials and Employees to stop the procurement of goods on a reimbursement basis, unless the circumstances warrant its application;



         b. 	Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to strictly enforce the provision that all payments must be made by check directly to the suppliers/dealers/creditors in the disbursement of government funds;

        c. 	Require the Municipal Accountant to deduct the corresponding withholding taxes in all disbursements required by the BIR; and



Adopt public bidding or alternative methods of procurement pursuant to the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 to ensure transparency, accountability and public monitoring in the procurement of goods and infrastructures.

To address the audit issue being raised, the Local Chief Executive requires:


a. 	The Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDC) to identify those barangays which are major potential tourism areas and funds are utilized for its improvements. 



b. 	To stop the practice of charging unnecessary expenditures under the 20% Development Fund.  Ensure that utilization of funds be maximized; 



c. 	Include only program and activities which are in accordance with DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular 2017-1; 



d. 	Demand the refund of the amount spent for the payment of wages from the officials and employees who approved  as these are not authorized to be charged against the Capital Outlay of the 20% Development Fund, otherwise, a Notice of Disallowance will be issued; and


e. 	Ensure that the 20% Development Fund is utilized within the purposes expressly prescribed by law not only to achieve desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcomes but also to avoid possible sanctions that may be imposed for non-compliance.

We have recommended Management the following courses of action:

a. 	Instruct all municipal officials and employees concerned to strictly adhere to the provisions of Executive Order No. 77 and other related laws, rules and regulations for expenses on travels and seminars;



b. 	Require the officials and employees concerned to submit the  required documents to support the claims on travelling and seminar expenses; 



c. 	Require the municipal officials/employees concerned to refund the amount in excess of the allowable and authorized travel rates as provided in EO No. 77.

Instruct the municipal officials and employees concerned to liquidate/settle their cash advances within the reglementary period;

Strictly observe the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 in the grant and utilization of cash advance and refrain from granting cash advances to other employees for special purposes; and strictly adhere to the provisions of Republic Act 9184 in the procurement of goods and services in order to avoid suspension/disallowance in audit;

Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that liquidations of cash advances are duly supported with complete documentation;

Stop the practice of granting additional cash advance to accountable officers with previous cash advances which remained unliquidated; and

Require the accountable officers concerned to maintain cashbooks and reconcile with the accounting records maintained by the Municipal Accountant.

We also recommended that Management stop the practice of granting cash advances to accountable officers for the purchase of goods and other undertakings utilizing the cash advance, but should be paid through the issuance of check. Further, ensure that funds received from PCSO, like STL, are treated as income upon receipt of the funds under the General Fund and provide appropriations in the utilization thereof.

Require the Municipal Officials and Employees concerned to   refund the: 
1)	Reimbursed amount of hotel accommodation in excess of the cost of lodging allowed in EO 298;
2)	Cost of van rental which is considered as one of those expenses categorized as unnecessary, unconscionable, extravagant and excessive pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012 is subject to an outright disallowance;
3)	Excess in the computation of traveling allowance; and
4)	Miscellaneous expenses incurred for meals and costs of assorted fish styro, assorted pasalubong and bread; 
b.	Maximize the use of its top of the line vehicle to achieve the purpose of the purchase and for the LGU to save its coffers from waste in matter of its utilization. 
